  ],
  "text": "Security audit of HTTP handler registration in Grafana Loki and Mimir repositories reveals multiple unauthenticated endpoints. In Mimir (grafana-mimir:pkg/api/api.go), the RegisterRoute and newRoute functions conditionally apply authentication middleware based on an auth parameter. When auth=false, handlers are registered without the AuthMiddleware wrapper. Unauthenticated endpoints include status endpoints (/api/v1/status/buildinfo, /api/v1/status/config, /api/v1/status/flags), operational endpoints (/memberlist, /services, /runtime_config), and ring status endpoints for various components (distributor, ingester, ruler, compactor, querier, query-scheduler). In Loki (grafana-loki), the Run() method in pkg/loki/loki.go registers multiple HTTP handlers directly via t.Server.HTTP.Path() without explicit authentication middleware. These include status handlers (versionHandler, readyHandler), configuration handlers (configHandler, tenantLimitsHandler), and operational handlers (LevelHandler, servicesHandler, formatQueryHandler). The distributor component (pkg/distributor/http.go) registers PushHandler and OTLPPushHandler without authentication, while the querier component (pkg/querier/http.go) registers multiple query handlers (RangeQueryHandler, InstantQueryHandler, LabelHandler, SeriesHandler, VolumeHandler, PatternsHandler, DetectedFieldsHandler) without middleware-based authentication. Both systems rely on external reverse proxies to enforce authentication and populate the X-Scope-OrgID header for multi-tenancy, rather than implementing authentication internally. This architecture assumes proper network configuration where Loki and Mimir services are only accessible through authenticated proxies, but the services themselves do not enforce authentication at the HTTP handler level."
}

